[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Investigating coverage issues**\n\nI need to figure out why the coverage isn't being tracked as expected. Maybe the coverage tool looks at runtime on `nativeTestCompile` and instruments the native-image build instead of the tests themselves? Perhaps tests are run to generate agent metadata before the build, but I’m curious if the `MethodHandles` are optimized.\n\nIt could be that not all tests are getting executed in the native image tests. I’ll need to examine the `build.gradle` for any omissions. The user’s report might link back to a previous dynamic-access issue, but our test may not be included. I’m also wondering about using Java reflection to access declared methods, although direct reflection usage is generally discouraged. Maybe the method handles aren’t capturing the calls as intended?\n\n**Exploring method handle instrumentation**\n\nI need to understand why `Class.forName` instrumentation isn't capturing certain methods. Could it be that the native image can't include a method because it's private and only accessible through `MethodHandle` or dynamic reflective access? I wonder if we need specific metadata for private methods in a native image.\n\nTests are executing under a JVM agent first, but the coverage might fail because, if there's an exception causing a test failure, it wouldn’t run properly. I could explore using Groovy's public API for invocation, since `PathSupport` implements `GroovyObject`. However, I need to test this out, but I'm not allowed to run any tests.\n\n**Considering testing options**\n\nThe rule is pretty clear: I can't compile or run tests myself. I wonder if I might be able to inspect things instead? Using `javap` could help me analyze without running anything. I could think about placing the test in the same package as the library to call `class$` directly, but the rule says to keep tests outside library packages.\n\nCr